        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "fbfd3d70"
      },
      "source": [
        "### How to adjust `src_pts` and `dst_pts`:\n",
        "\n",
        "1.  **`src_pts`**: These are the four points in your original `images.jpg` that define the area you want to 'straighten out' or transform. They should ideally be the corners of a rectangular object that appears distorted in the original image (e.g., a book cover, a document on a table).\n",
        "    *   You need to visually identify these points in your `images.jpg` and replace the placeholder coordinates `[100, 100]`, `[500, 100]`, etc., with the actual (x, y) coordinates of those corners.\n",
        "    *   The order matters: typically, you'd go top-left, top-right, bottom-right, bottom-left, but as long as the order corresponds to `dst_pts`, it will work.\n",
        "\n",
        "2.  **`dst_pts`**: These are the four points in the *output* image where the `src_pts` will be mapped to. For a common scenario like flattening a document, you'd want these to form a perfect rectangle. Adjust `width` and `height` variables to define the desired dimensions of your output image.\n",
        "\n",
        "If you need help identifying the coordinates, you can use image editing software or write a small script to click on points in the image to get their coordinates."
      ]
    }
  ]
